At work, sometimes we would like to see the distribution of two features over our millions of players. Scatterplots fail miserably because they:

  • get saturated very quickly, making it impossible to see anything other than a blob
  • crawl to a halt after a few ten of thousands of data points.

So we ended up not using them much. However, I recently discovered an awesome library called datashader that would accomplish exactly that - visualize the density of arbitrary large amounts of data. Coupled with Bokeh, we can zoom in and out of the chart, and the densities will be dynamically updated to only account for the current visible region.

The following is an example that generate 10 million data points from a mixture of 4 gaussians. We plot the density at the very end. This example borrows heavily from the following Continuum notebooks:

  • https://anaconda.org/jbednar/nyc_taxi/notebook
  • https://anaconda.org/jbednar/osm/notebook

We first calculate the covariance matrix of our gaussians, given the parameters cov_cfg. Then we sample our data points and write them in batches to different files.

In [1]:
%matplotlib inline
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import dask.dataframe as dd
from dask.diagnostics import ProgressBar, Profiler, ResourceProfiler, visualize

#generate the covariance matrix of a bivariate gaussian, given the means and the angle of rotation of the eigenvectors
def gencov(u1, u2, theta):
    theta = np.radians(theta)
    base = np.matrix(np.diag([u1, u2]))
    c, s = np.cos(theta), np.sin(theta)
    rot = np.matrix('{} {}; {} {}'.format(c, -s, s, c))
    return rot*base*rot.T

mean = [[0, 0], [5,6], [-3, -4], [-10, -10]]
cov_cfg = [[10,20,20], [6, 4, 60], [25, 20, 30], [50, 5, 110]]
cov = [gencov(*c) for c in cov_cfg]
prob = [0.4, 0.3, 0.2, 0.1]

choices = len(mean)
sample_size = 10000000
batches = 10
samples_per_batch = int(sample_size/batches)

#generate batches of data, and write each to a separate file
for i in range(batches):
    freq = np.bincount(np.random.choice(choices, samples_per_batch, p=prob))
    samples = np.vstack([np.random.multivariate_normal(mean[i], cov[i], f) for i, f in enumerate(freq)])
    df = pd.DataFrame(samples, columns=['x', 'y'])
    filename = 'gaussian' + str(i) + '.h5'
    df.index = range(i*samples_per_batch, (i+1)*samples_per_batch)
    df.to_hdf(filename, key='/a', format='table')

We use dask to read the data, because it is more accommdating to pandas for larger datasets:

We calculate the bounds of our initial plot below (at least 5 standard deviations from the mean of each gaussian).

In [4]:
m = np.array(mean)
sd2 = 5*np.sqrt(np.repeat(np.reshape(np.array(cov_cfg)[:, :-1].max(1), (-1,1)), 2, axis=1))
max_xy = (m+sd2).max(0)
min_xy = (m-sd2).min(0)
bounds = np.vstack([min_xy, max_xy])
print(bounds)

In [5]:
import datashader as ds
from datashader import transfer_functions as tf
from bokeh.plotting import figure, output_notebook, show
from datashader.colors import colormap_select, Greys9, Hot, viridis, inferno
from datashader.bokeh_ext import InteractiveImage
import sys

output_notebook()

plot_width = 500
plot_height = 500
x_range = list(bounds[:, 0])
y_range = list(bounds[:, 1])

def base_plot(tools='pan,wheel_zoom,reset',plot_width=plot_width, plot_height=plot_height, **plot_args):
    p = figure(tools=tools, plot_width=plot_width, plot_height=plot_height,
        x_range=x_range, y_range=y_range, outline_line_color=None,
        min_border=0, min_border_left=0, min_border_right=0,
        min_border_top=0, min_border_bottom=0, **plot_args)
    
    #p.axis.visible = False
    p.xgrid.grid_line_color = None
    p.ygrid.grid_line_color = None
    return p

def create_image(x_range, y_range, w=plot_width, h=plot_height):
    cvs = ds.Canvas(plot_width=w, plot_height=h, x_range=x_range, y_range=y_range)
    with ProgressBar() as pbar:
        agg = cvs.points(df, 'x', 'y',  ds.count())
        print(sys.getsizeof(agg))
    img = tf.shade(agg, cmap=Hot, how='eq_hist')
    return tf.dynspread(img, threshold=0.5, max_px=4)


p = base_plot(background_fill_color='black')
InteractiveImage(p, create_image)

Out[5]:

As the progress bar shows above, it barely took datashader anytime to preprocess the data for plotting. Try plotting a 10-million scatter plot!

The chart doesn't update dynamically when you zoom in outside the local environment, but you can already get an idea of the distribution from the chart above. We are just scratching the surface of what datashader is capable of, though.

Next steps

  • Right now all data belongs to the same class. We can add additional labels and plot them with another color to see how it looks.
  • Try different aggregation functions in datashader.
  • Right now updating the view can take a few seconds. Can we make it faster?
